contact each other anymore.

12:35.367 --> 12:36.267
(Suzanne)
No, I get it.

12:36.367 --> 12:38.733
I will miss seeing your face

12:38.833 --> 12:40.833
because it's just
really great-looking.

12:40.933 --> 12:42.833
- Good-bye.
- Bye, Ace Shrift.

12:42.933 --> 12:44.167
Oh!

12:44.267 --> 12:47.067
The cat has been fished!
[laughs]

12:47.100 --> 12:47.867
I was terrified!

12:47.967 --> 12:49.567
That whole time you were like,

12:49.667 --> 12:50.767
"I'm not Ace Shrift,
I'm Joe Dale,"

12:50.867 --> 12:52.100
I was like, "What are you doing?

12:52.200 --> 12:53.900
You're gonna give away
the whole catfish thing."

12:54.067 --> 12:55.300
[sighs] Thank you
for ending it like that.

12:55.400 --> 12:57.867
Just ending it.
It's over.

12:57.967 --> 13:00.533
That's the best $40,000
I've ever spent in my life.

13:00.633 --> 13:02.067
That was
a terrific investment.

13:02.133 --> 13:03.600
- Yes.
- Yeah.

13:03.700 --> 13:05.067
Well, you guys probably
have a lot going on and--

13:05.100 --> 13:07.800
- That's right.
- No, actually, no.

13:07.900 --> 13:10.067
- Yeah, we should get going.
- Yeah.

13:10.100 --> 13:13.567
Catfishing, just as Joe Dale Jr.
so eloquently put it,

13:13.667 --> 13:17.700
begins with dishonesty
and ends up in a bad spot.

13:17.800 --> 13:19.967
But there's a part
in the middle there

13:20.067 --> 13:22.733
where the catfisher tricks
his ex-wife into believing

13:22.833 --> 13:25.733
that she will find happiness
with some fictitious person,

13:25.833 --> 13:27.200
and though it's brief--

13:27.300 --> 13:29.933
and in retrospect,
it's pretty disgusting--

13:30.067 --> 13:30.600
in the moment,

13:30.700 --> 13:34.467
it's breathtaking.

13:34.567 --> 13:37.233
Catfishing, three stars.

13:39.500 --> 13:41.833
What is my next review,
please, A.J.?

13:41.933 --> 13:43.700
[trumpet fanfare]
- What are you doing?

13:43.800 --> 13:45.600
Well, Forrest, did you know
that in Civil War times

13:45.700 --> 13:47.267
people used to write letters
to each other

13:47.367 --> 13:48.533
on thinly sliced trees?

13:48.633 --> 13:50.900
- Paper, I know all about paper.
- Oh.

13:51.067 --> 13:52.100
- Yeah, big fan.
- [gasps]

13:52.200 --> 13:54.067
Our very first ever
old person pen pal...

13:54.100 --> 13:56.100
Mm-hmm.

13:56.200 --> 13:57.300
Is from Steamboat Springs,
Colorado.

13:57.400 --> 13:59.367
Oh, let me guess the zip code,

13:59.467 --> 14:01.800
80477.

14:01.900 --> 14:02.700
That actually was right.

14:02.800 --> 14:04.233
Yeah, I know all the zip codes.

14:04.333 --> 14:05.300
That's weird.

14:05.400 --> 14:07.800
"Dear Forrest MacNeil,

14:07.900 --> 14:08.667
"By the time you read this,

14:08.767 --> 14:10.733
- I'll be dead."
- Wow.

14:10.833 --> 14:12.567
"The gals
in my stitch-n-bitch group

14:12.667 --> 14:14.167
"are devastated about it

14:14.267 --> 14:16.733
"because they believe
my awful ghost will haunt them.

14:16.833 --> 14:19.667
"What's it like to spend
the night in a haunted house?

14:19.767 --> 14:22.333
Sincerely, I.L. Salazar."

14:22.433 --> 14:23.300
Huh.

14:23.400 --> 14:25.167
Well, here I go to find out

14:25.267 --> 14:27.267
what it's like to spend a night
in a haunted house.

14:27.367 --> 14:28.900
Might be
some ghosts there.

14:29.067 --> 14:32.067
(Forrest)
There is
a very creepy abandoned house

14:32.100 --> 14:33.733
in the neighborhood
where I grew up,

14:33.833 --> 14:34.800
and I headed there with my dad

14:34.900 --> 14:37.700
for the purposes
of father-son bonding

14:37.800 --> 14:39.867
and also because I was scared.

14:39.967 --> 14:41.533
I had forgotten
about the old Durretz house

14:41.633 --> 14:45.533
and its outlandish
and gruesome tale.

14:45.633 --> 14:47.767
A century ago,
we are told,

14:47.867 --> 14:50.967
a farmer murdered
his entire extended family,

14:51.067 --> 14:54.433
and he ground them up, and
then he fed them to his pigs.

14:54.533 --> 14:57.133
50 years after that,
they say,

14:57.233 --> 15:00.833
the house became haunted
by an unrelated ghost.

15:00.933 --> 15:02.800
[sirens wail]

15:02.900 --> 15:06.433
[mysterious music]

15:06.533 --> 15:09.667
*

15:09.767 --> 15:12.700
(Forrest)
Ghosts may or may not exist,

15:12.800 --> 15:16.533
but in our world, they do not.

15:16.633 --> 15:18.067
Our evening
in the Durretz house

15:18.100 --> 15:19.833
was therefore deeply boring,

15:19.933 --> 15:22.533
affording me the soundest sleep
I'd had in weeks.

15:22.633 --> 15:23.700
[snoring]

15:23.800 --> 15:26.200
But then...

15:26.300 --> 15:27.800
something happened.

15:27.900 --> 15:30.833
[snoring continues]

15:33.100 --> 15:34.067
[gasps]

15:36.933 --> 15:39.067
(Forrest)
Not an encounter
with the earthbound soul

15:39.167 --> 15:43.067
of a dead person
but an important idea.

15:43.133 --> 15:46.633
Perhaps inspired by my recent
experience with catfishing,

15:46.733 --> 15:48.500
I realized that
I did know a house

15:48.600 --> 15:52.133
that was actually haunted.

15:52.233 --> 15:54.200
This is the house where I lived
with my ex-wife, Suzanne,

15:54.300 --> 15:58.300
and my son, Eric.

15:58.400 --> 16:02.233
(Forrest)
This house holds the ghost
of what my life used to be.

16:02.333 --> 16:04.667
(Gene)
Forrest!

16:04.767 --> 16:06.067
(Forrest)
Gene!

16:06.100 --> 16:08.067
[chuckles]
You're kidding me.

16:08.167 --> 16:10.867
(Forrest)
My old neighbor
and former best friend, Gene,

16:10.967 --> 16:13.733
was like a vision
from a life I had lost.

16:13.833 --> 16:15.567
It's me, Forrest.

16:15.667 --> 16:17.533
Forrest MacNeil
from the past.

16:17.633 --> 16:18.833
Yeah, I remember.

16:18.933 --> 16:21.767
I'm just visiting
the old house.

16:21.867 --> 16:23.367
You're visiting
the old house right now?

16:23.467 --> 16:24.100
Yeah, mm-hmm.

16:24.200 --> 16:26.767
Hmm.

16:26.867 --> 16:29.133
Well, the people that live there
are on vacation,

16:29.233 --> 16:30.867
so you might want to come back
during the daytime

16:30.967 --> 16:35.833
'cause it's, uh...
bad to come at midnight.

16:35.933 --> 16:37.633
I understand.

16:37.733 --> 16:41.967
Okay, I guess this isn't really
my place anymore, huh?

16:42.067 --> 16:44.767
No, you--
you sold it.

16:44.867 --> 16:48.567
It was great
to see you again.

16:48.667 --> 16:50.267
And--and you're leaving now?

16:50.367 --> 16:52.133
Now, yes.

16:52.233 --> 16:54.067
I believe
I will see you again.

16:54.133 --> 16:55.667
[chuckles]

16:55.767 --> 17:01.400
*

17:01.500 --> 17:02.533
Oh, wow.

17:02.633 --> 17:05.200
The lock on this window
was always broken,

17:05.300 --> 17:06.800
so, assuming they
haven't fixed it,

17:06.900 --> 17:10.233
I should be able
to very carefully, very--

17:10.333 --> 17:12.833
[glass breaking]
- Aw, [bleep] [bleep]!

17:12.933 --> 17:14.633
God damn it.

17:14.733 --> 17:18.933
I'm in.
Come in.

17:19.067 --> 17:21.400
(Forrest)
My quest to spend a night

17:21.500 --> 17:24.800
in a haunted house had
brought me to hallowed ground.

17:24.900 --> 17:26.833
[door closes]

17:26.933 --> 17:32.067
This is where I lived with
my boy and the love of my live.

17:32.133 --> 17:34.533
They've made a lot
of bad choices here.

17:34.633 --> 17:37.500
It's terrible.

17:37.600 --> 17:42.367
Do they have any idea what came
before them in this space?

17:42.467 --> 17:44.767
Do they even care?
I don't know.

17:44.867 --> 17:48.467
But I do know they need to get
rid of that chair right away.

17:53.267 --> 17:55.967
Mmm!

17:56.067 --> 17:57.200
I feel like there's a realm

17:57.300 --> 18:02.733
where we didn't get divorced
right here.

18:02.833 --> 18:04.367
Suzanne and I
are still married.

18:04.467 --> 18:07.100
[sighs]

18:11.867 --> 18:14.067
There was a murder
in this kitchen,

18:14.133 --> 18:15.533
the murder of a marriage.

18:15.633 --> 18:19.533
[discordant piano notes]

18:19.633 --> 18:23.233
Oh, give me the strength
to go upstairs.

18:23.333 --> 18:24.200
Oh.

18:27.733 --> 18:29.067
[whispers]
What if I walk into that bedroom

18:29.167 --> 18:31.733
and Suzanne and I
are in there?

18:34.400 --> 18:36.167
Nope.

18:40.733 --> 18:42.267
It occurs to me now

18:42.367 --> 18:46.700
that there is a ghost
haunting this house tonight.

18:46.800 --> 18:48.200
It's me.

18:48.300 --> 18:50.833
Boo!

18:50.933 --> 18:52.100
(Forrest)
I had hoped that the alcohol

18:52.200 --> 18:53.800
would act
as a kind of talisman...

18:53.900 --> 18:55.167
Suzanne.

18:55.267 --> 18:56.833
(Forrest)
Warding off
the frightening specter

18:56.933 --> 18:58.067
of my slaughtered former life.

19:01.167 --> 19:04.433
But it only brought on
greater horrors.

19:04.533 --> 19:06.433
[creak]

19:06.533 --> 19:08.133
What was that?

19:09.767 --> 19:11.733
Did you hear that?

19:13.167 --> 19:14.733
[phone ringing]
- Oh!

19:17.667 --> 19:20.933
- Hello?
- [speaking foreign language]

19:21.067 --> 19:24.967
Who are you?
What do you want?

19:25.067 --> 19:26.800
Is that the language
they speak in hell?

19:26.900 --> 19:29.067
- [bleep].
[phone ringing]

19:29.133 --> 19:30.367
We got to get out of here.

19:30.467 --> 19:32.900
(Forrest)
And the horrors had just begun.

19:33.067 --> 19:35.133
[phone ringing]

19:40.833 --> 19:41.733
Gene?

19:41.833 --> 19:45.200
[phone continues ringing]

19:47.400 --> 19:49.100
- [screams]
- [screams]

19:49.200 --> 19:50.667
[knife stabs Forrest]

19:50.767 --> 19:52.667
Oh, God.
Oh!

19:55.067 --> 19:56.400
Oh.

19:56.500 --> 19:57.533
[shouting in native language]

19:57.633 --> 20:02.300
[groaning]

20:02.400 --> 20:04.933
Why did you do that to me?

20:05.033 --> 20:06.500
[crying]
Oh, God!

20:06.600 --> 20:07.300
Aah!

20:07.400 --> 20:10.500
[speaking native language]

20:10.600 --> 20:13.800
[sighs]

20:13.900 --> 20:16.167
That woman was Grandma Choi,
the matriarch of the family

20:16.267 --> 20:18.733
that bought the house
from Suzanne.

20:18.833 --> 20:20.533
She's afraid of flying,
so she didn't join

20:20.633 --> 20:22.433
the rest of her family
in Hawaii.

20:22.533 --> 20:24.633
She unfortunately mistook me
for an intruder

20:24.733 --> 20:27.000
and stabbed me
just above the navel,

20:27.100 --> 20:29.833
puncturing my large intestine.

20:29.933 --> 20:32.033
Oh, my God, Forrest.

20:32.133 --> 20:35.033
Well, I'm building up a pretty
good tolerance to physical pain,

20:35.133 --> 20:37.600
so no big deal.

20:37.700 --> 20:40.033
Now, my experience
with haunted houses taught me

20:40.133 --> 20:41.833
that we create phantoms

20:41.933 --> 20:45.233
to avoid thinking about our own
frightening or sad realities.

20:45.333 --> 20:49.867
Spending a night
in a haunted house, one star.

20:54.500 --> 20:55.933
So what happened to your dad?

20:56.033 --> 20:57.367
What do you mean?

20:57.467 --> 21:00.067
You left him
to spend a night alone

21:00.133 --> 21:02.967
in a real haunted house.

21:03.067 --> 21:04.333
Oh, yeah.

21:04.433 --> 21:06.200
Huh.

21:14.167 --> 21:15.467
Ooh, look in here.

21:15.567 --> 21:17.333
Why would a ghost choose
to live here, you know?

21:17.433 --> 21:18.533
Why do we assume
that ghosts want to live

21:18.633 --> 21:19.533
in dilapidated houses?

21:19.633 --> 21:21.167
Ghosts can go anywhere,
can't they?

21:21.267 --> 21:22.267
Yes.

21:22.367 --> 21:23.267
If I were a ghost,
I'd probably go live

21:23.367 --> 21:24.900
in Buckingham Palace.

21:25.067 --> 21:26.733
I think they like
the free maintenance.

21:26.833 --> 21:27.133
[laughs]
